https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/linux-incident-response-sticky-bits-suid-sgid-taz-wake-o9hee/

Sticky: Mainly used on folders in order to avoid deletion of a folder and it’s content by other users though they having write permissions on the folder contents. If Sticky bit is enabled on a folder (t,1 values)
Cmd: chmod o+t /mydir

chmod 4755 => suid

chmod 2755 => sgid

chmod 1755 => sticky


SUID: SUID is defined as giving temporary permissions to a user to run a program/file 
with the permissions of the file owner rather that the user who runs it.(value 4)

command: chmod u+s /usr/bin/passwd

SGID(2) users will get file Group’s permissions when executing a Folder/file/program/command.
Value( 2)command: chmod g+s /mydir
UMASK:022 
